Finally, we remark here that nearly all springs have a certain warmth at their first rise; and indeed the heat ol spring-water just escaping from the earth can be quite sensibly lelt in winter when the hand is immersed in it. No doubt the aerial particles which descend with rain-water into the earth effervesce in an obscure motion with the saline-sulphureous particles of which nearly every kind ol earth is composed3 and consequently a certain warmth is produced, on which the growth of vegetables depends, as hasbeen else· where shown.
